<subSubSection id="E7A2B298FFD678696FBE1D2BFB777F42" box="[199,1214,1554,1579]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="AF07E113FFD678696FBE1D2BFB777F42" blockId="35.[151,1436,834,1651]" box="[199,1214,1554,1579]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis id="9DCC3D01FFD678696FBE1D2BFE877F43" bold="true" box="[199,334,1555,1579]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of this species is descriptive for the recurved apex of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E7A2B298FFD678696FBE1D0FFB6E7F1A" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="AF07E113FFD678696FBE1D0FFB6E7F1A" blockId="35.[151,1436,834,1651]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis id="9DCC3D01FFD678696FBE1D0FFEF47F27" bold="true" box="[199,317,1591,1615]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Remarks:</emphasis>
This species has genitalia features most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="68B89A90FFD678696CF01D0FFBDC7F26" authorityName="Nielson" authorityYear="2011" box="[905,1045,1590,1614]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Evansolidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilitas">
<emphasis id="9DCC3D01FFD678696CF01D0FFC537F26" box="[905,922,1591,1614]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="9DCC3D01FFD678696CD01D0EFBDC7F26" box="[937,1045,1590,1614]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">gracilitas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can be easily separated by the strongly recurved apex of the aedeagus with very small spines on the distal third of the shaft.
</paragraph>
